The article discusses the importance of physical fitness and sports, particularly in the context of the COVID-19 pandemic. It highlights the decrease in physical activity rates, especially among groups at high risk for COVID-19, and the socioeconomic disparities that have exacerbated this problem. The article emphasizes the need for equitable solutions to ensure that all Americans have access to opportunities for physical activity. It also mentions the various health benefits of being physically active, such as reducing the risk of chronic diseases, improving sleep, and enhancing mental health. The article mentions initiatives and campaigns aimed at increasing physical activity, including the renewal of the President's Council on Sports, Fitness & Nutrition and the "Active People, Healthy Nation" initiative. It encourages individuals to engage in physical activities such as walking, hiking, fitness classes, and joining sports teams. The article concludes with a proclamation by President Joseph R. Biden Jr. declaring May 2022 as National Physical Fitness and Sports Month, calling upon Americans to prioritize daily physical activity and support efforts to increase access to sports opportunities in their communities.